ould use Groovy MOP instead—though it could lead to issues. It seems I may need to explain why certain methods are left uncovered, but modifying tests to instantiate subclasses feels impossible. Perhaps it’s best to focus on keeping the updates concise without unnecessary edits. I might also look at the git diff to confirm my changes.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "I re-checked the active class and the remaining dynamic-access site:\n\n```text\nio.restassured.internal.RequestSpecificationImpl$_applyPathParamsAndSendRequest_closure33.class$\n  -> java.lang.Class#forName(String)\n```\n\nFor `rest-assured-5.5.0`, `closure33` is the Groovy comparator used here:\n\n```groovy\nfilters = filters.toSorted { f1, f2 -> getFilterOrder(f1) <=> getFilterOrder(f2) }\n```\n\nThe dedicated test already added:\n\n```text\ntests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io_rest_assured/rest_assured/RequestSpecificationImplInner_applyPathParamsAndSendRequest_closure33Test.java\n```\n\nexercises that supported public API path by sending a path-parameterized request with multiple `OrderedFilter` instances, forcing filter sorting and comparator execution.\n\nThe still-uncovered call site is in Groovy’s synthetic `class$(String)` helper. Inspecting the compiled bytecode shows the actual comparator path uses direct class literals (`ldc`) and does not call `class$`. Therefore, the only practical way to execute `class$` would be to artificially invoke the internal synthetic helper method, e.g. through reflection or other implementation-detail access. That would violate the rules requiring supported behavior through Rest Assured’s normal public API and avoiding direct reflection.\n\nSo I did not add another artificial test. The call site appears unreachable through supported public API behavior for this artifact version.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_075d40d8f56de983016a27393c6620819388b348d09af07dca\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provi